summary.seg: Emmanuel College, MS 13 was probably copied in the 11th or 12th century, and is the second volume of a set of two (the first being Emmanuel MS 12). It contains 15 homilies by the Patriarch of Constantinople, John Chrysostom, In Matthaeum homiliae (16-24, 30-35) . Homilies 25-29 were not copied, as hom. 30-35 are numbered as κεʹ-λʹ, and consistently with the first group. Emmanuel MSS 12-15 contain homilies to the Gospel of Matthew by Chrysostom and share a common provenance and history, and were used by Frederick Field for his edition of the homilies (Cambridge 1839; see vol. 1, p. XVIII and XXI).

Hom. 30: ff. 277r-285v with two lacunae: f. [282]v ends at PG 57, 366 line 55 τοῖς ἀσθενέστερον ἔτι διακειμένοις, f. [283]r starts from 367 line 38 Ἱερε]μίας περίζωμα τὸν λαόν φησι, f. [284]v ends at 369 line 17 κέχρηνται τῆ σπουδῆ, f. 285r starts from 370 line 13 ὁ προφήτης ἀσκεῖν ἐκέλευσε

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of variable thickness and medium quality.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 21 quires, of which two are ternia and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 98-1 ff. 239-245 The third folio has been lost, with loss of text
Quire 148-1 ff. 278-[284] The sixth folio has been lost, with loss of text
Quire 158-1 ff. 285-[291] The first folio has been lost, with loss of text

signatures.p: Signatures in Greek numerals in brown ink on last verso, lower internal corner, from quire 1 (f. [184]v) from κδʹ to μδʹ, continuing from Emmanuel MS 12.
One signature in Greek numerals (κδʹ) in light-brown ink on f. 1r.
A modern signatures in Greek numerals in pencil on first recto from quire 2.

supportDesc.condition: There are holes in some folios (e.g. ff. [280], [286]). The outer margins of ff. 314 and [336-337] have been cut away. There is some cockling, creasing, water staining, drops of wax and areas of dirt. Water staining has contributed to occasional abrasion of text, and there is significant abrasion to f. [337]v.

layoutDesc.layout:
Two columns of 30 lines. 287 185
Pricking does not survive. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 5, type Leroy 44C2 . Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The manuscript is written in a mixed minuscule script, by the same hand of Emmanuel MS 12.

decoDesc.decoNote: Headpieces outlined in red ink at the beginning of each homily, from f. [184]v.
Major decarated initials of homilies in red ink from f. [184]v.
Minor initials in red ink throughout the manuscript.

additions.p: A notes on f. [iii] verso: A reference to the edition by Henry Savile, Sancti Ioannis Chrysostomi opera Graece, Eton College, 1612-13: Vide Editionem Sancti Chrysostomi Etonae impressam curante Henrico Savilio Anno MDCXII. Vol. 2. p. 113. l. 35 ἀλλὰ καὶ λίθων καὶ πάσης εὐκόλως κ.τ.λ.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over millboards, sewn with cord on single raised supports, boards attached with laced-in slips Separate-sewn endbands, the outermost and the pastedowns of marbled paper. Hatched leather on the boards, with decorative gold tooling on boards and spine. The title Chrysostomi Homiliae Vol. II. MS is tooled in gold on black labels on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches.
binding.condition: The left outer joint is partially split at the tail and both endcaps are damaged. The leather covering has become flaky.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in in the 11th or 12th century.
history.provenance:
As Emmanuel MS 12, the manuscript comes from the Monastery of Kastamoniti of Mount Athos. The manuscript was bought by
Anthony Askew (1722-1774) Askew, Anthony, 1722-1774, physician and book collector, in his travel to the Mt Athos. After his death, the manuscripts were sold by G. Leigh and J. Sotheby in the auction of his library in 1785 (Lot. n. 612), but his son
Adam Askew (1752-1844) Askew, Adam 1752-1844 was able to get possession of them again and gave them to
Samuel Parr (1747-1825) Parr, Samuel, 1747-1825 and eventually presented by him to Emmanuel College in 1814, as in the note on f. [iii] verso.

acquisition.p: Eventually presented to Emmanuel College by Samuel Parr in 1814.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 11-12.
